1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,029
The county offered the same one hundred
and four acres three times. Three times

2
00:00:05,029 --> 00:00:10,121
the courthouse steps went quiet when the
auctioneer asked for an opening bid. At

3
00:00:10,121 --> 00:00:14,570
the fourth sale, in March, a
thirty-eight-year-old widow named Corinne

4
00:00:14,570 --> 00:00:19,276
Ashbury raised her card and said
ninety-one thousand four hundred dollars.

5
00:00:19,276 --> 00:00:23,982
It was very close to every cent her
husband's life insurance had ever paid

6
00:00:23,982 --> 00:00:24,240
her.

7
00:00:24,240 --> 00:00:30,615
For twenty-two years the kudzu had been
taking that place the way still water

8
00:00:30,615 --> 00:00:37,325
takes a low field. First the fence line.
Then the hay barn. Then the shape of the

9
00:00:37,325 --> 00:00:44,035
hills, until the whole property read from
the highway as one long green wave that

10
00:00:44,035 --> 00:00:48,480
changed color with the season and never
changed shape.

11
00:00:48,480 --> 00:00:53,530
Somebody near the back laughed, and then
two more. Every man on those steps had

12
00:00:53,530 --> 00:00:58,516
fought the vines on his own ground and
knew how that story ended. What was out

13
00:00:58,516 --> 00:01:03,760
there had stopped being a weed problem a
long time ago. It had become a landscape.

14
00:01:03,760 --> 00:01:08,468
Not one person in that room knew that
under the vines, nine trees were still

15
00:01:08,468 --> 00:01:11,920
alive. Neither did the woman who had just
paid for them.

16
00:01:11,920 --> 00:01:15,760
Three weeks later she walked eighty-three
goats down the slope.

17
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:21,582
In Luke, chapter thirteen, the Lord
Himself told about a tree that had borne

18
00:01:21,582 --> 00:01:27,637
nothing for three years, and about the
man who asked for one more season before

19
00:01:27,637 --> 00:01:33,692
it came down. *Let it alone this year
also, till I shall dig about it, and dung

20
00:01:33,692 --> 00:01:34,080
it.*.

21
00:01:34,080 --> 00:01:38,800
Corinne Ashbury had three growing
seasons. Would that be enough?

22
00:01:38,800 --> 00:01:43,952
Georgia tax sales happen on the first
Tuesday of the month, on the courthouse

23
00:01:43,952 --> 00:01:48,900
steps. That Tuesday in March the wind
came down the street in front of the

24
00:01:48,900 --> 00:01:53,713
Gilmer County courthouse cold enough that
the auctioneer read the parcel

25
00:01:53,713 --> 00:01:58,933
description with his collar up, and the
men standing there kept their hands in

26
00:01:58,933 --> 00:02:04,355
their pockets, which is its own kind of
bidding. They all knew it. They called it

27
00:02:04,355 --> 00:02:05,440
the kudzu place.

28
00:02:05,440 --> 00:02:10,538
Corinne Ashbury had spent twelve years as
a claims adjuster in Atlanta. Her job was

29
00:02:10,538 --> 00:02:15,200
to stand in other people's driveways
after the worst week of their lives and

30
00:02:15,200 --> 00:02:19,738
write down a number for what they had
lost. Three years a widow. She wrote

31
00:02:19,738 --> 00:02:24,650
everything down and did not talk much,
and people often mistook the second thing

32
00:02:24,650 --> 00:02:25,520
for the first.

33
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:30,492
Nolan Ashbury had been her husband for
eleven years. He died on a January

34
00:02:30,492 --> 00:02:35,741
morning, his heart, before the ambulance
got up their street, and that is the

35
00:02:35,741 --> 00:02:41,197
whole of it, because she never told it
longer than that to anybody. What he left

36
00:02:41,197 --> 00:02:43,200
behind was a boy and a check.

37
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:47,811
The boy was Otis, eight years old,
waiting out of the wind in the courthouse

38
00:02:47,811 --> 00:02:52,605
hallway with a pencil box flat on his
knees, counting ceiling tiles. He counted

39
00:02:52,605 --> 00:02:54,880
things the way other children hummed.

40
00:02:54,880 --> 00:03:00,088
The parcel was one hundred and four acres
east of the county line, with no

41
00:03:00,088 --> 00:03:05,724
productive use in the record. Somebody a
generation ago had planted kudzu on the

42
00:03:05,724 --> 00:03:11,218
road bank to hold the soil, which is what
people were told to do once, and the

43
00:03:11,218 --> 00:03:16,640
vines did exactly what they were asked
and then kept going. Twenty-two years.

44
00:03:16,640 --> 00:03:21,856
When the auctioneer asked for an opening
bid the fourth time, she said the number

45
00:03:21,856 --> 00:03:26,877
without raising her voice, and the gavel
came down on ninety-one thousand four

46
00:03:26,877 --> 00:03:27,920
hundred dollars.

47
00:03:27,920 --> 00:03:33,437
She did not buy it to farm it. She had
driven past that wall of vines every

48
00:03:33,437 --> 00:03:38,804
month for two years on her way to a
claims office in Ellijay, and a thing

49
00:03:38,804 --> 00:03:44,843
valued at nothing had begun to look like
a thing nobody had looked at. That is not

50
00:03:44,843 --> 00:03:50,658
agriculture. That is a woman who priced
losses for a living, buying the largest

51
00:03:50,658 --> 00:03:52,000
one in the county.

52
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:58,882
What she had, besides the deed, was a
legal pad out of the claims office with a

53
00:03:58,882 --> 00:04:05,588
column of figures down one side and the
word goats written across the top and

54
00:04:05,588 --> 00:04:10,000
underlined twice. Goats eat kudzu. Goats
prefer it.

55
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:15,834
There was a condition, and she understood
it before signing. The land came in under

56
00:04:15,834 --> 00:04:21,029
a conservation use covenant, which lets
working ground be taxed as working

57
00:04:21,029 --> 00:04:26,650
ground. To keep it she had to show real
agricultural use, and a county appraiser

58
00:04:26,650 --> 00:04:31,986
would walk the kudzu himself in the
spring of the fourth year. Three growing

59
00:04:31,986 --> 00:04:37,607
seasons. If the covenant broke, the back
taxes and the penalty came due at once,

60
00:04:37,607 --> 00:04:40,880
and no version of her arithmetic survived
that.

61
00:04:40,880 --> 00:04:45,308
After the ninety-one thousand four
hundred dollars, after the fees and the

62
00:04:45,308 --> 00:04:50,160
transfer, what was left would buy a used
stock trailer, a pair of school shoes in

63
00:04:50,160 --> 00:04:53,920
September, and something under half the
goats on the legal pad.

64
00:04:53,920 --> 00:04:58,889
She signed her name, took the key to a
gate nobody had opened in twenty-two

65
00:04:58,889 --> 00:05:03,924
years, and drove out toward the only
thing the highway would show her, which

66
00:05:03,924 --> 00:05:05,200
was a single color.

67
00:05:05,200 --> 00:05:09,862
If you have ever been told that the thing
you wanted to save was not worth saving,

68
00:05:09,862 --> 00:05:14,007
then you already know exactly how she
felt sitting in that truck with the

69
00:05:14,007 --> 00:05:14,640
engine off.

70
00:05:14,640 --> 00:05:20,663
The first walk in got her four hundred
yards in an afternoon. The vines had gone

71
00:05:20,663 --> 00:05:26,762
over the fence and made a wall of it, so
she went in where a deer went in, on her

72
00:05:26,762 --> 00:05:32,708
hands and knees, Otis behind her. Under
the leaves it was cool and dim, a green

73
00:05:32,708 --> 00:05:38,655
ceiling twenty feet up in places, holding
the light out. The air smelled of wet

74
00:05:38,655 --> 00:05:44,601
leaf and rot and, once, of something dry
and sweet, the way a pecan husk smells

75
00:05:44,601 --> 00:05:45,440
after rain.

76
00:05:45,440 --> 00:05:51,124
She found the hay barn by walking into
it. Otis found eleven fence posts and

77
00:05:51,124 --> 00:05:52,640
reported the number.

78
00:05:52,640 --> 00:05:57,490
From the crown of the slope the whole of
it showed at once, and that was the

79
00:05:57,490 --> 00:06:02,598
problem. One hundred and four acres of
kudzu reads as a single object, and there

80
00:06:02,598 --> 00:06:05,120
is nowhere on a single object to start.

81
00:06:05,120 --> 00:06:10,522
Burl Tannehill was seventy-one, had run
goats on that ridge since his grandfather

82
00:06:10,522 --> 00:06:15,518
ran them, and was the only man in the
county who did not laugh. He told her

83
00:06:15,518 --> 00:06:20,582
what goats do, which is browse, up and
out, leaf and vine and bark, and what

84
00:06:20,582 --> 00:06:24,971
goats do not do, which is anything a
person counts on. He sold her

85
00:06:24,971 --> 00:06:29,360
eighty-three head at a price fair to both
and generous to neither.

86
00:06:29,360 --> 00:06:34,758
He also handed her a brass bell on a worn
strap and said to hang it on the lead

87
00:06:34,758 --> 00:06:40,087
doe. The doe was Pepper, gray-muzzled,
who came off his trailer like she owned

88
00:06:40,087 --> 00:06:45,416
it, and the herd followed. In fog, Burl
said, the eyes are no good to anybody.

89
00:06:45,416 --> 00:06:46,800
The ears still work.

90
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:52,149
They set electric netting and split the
near slope into paddocks of four acres.

91
00:06:52,149 --> 00:06:57,360
Eight to ten goats to the acre, he said,
and move them before they get bored.

92
00:06:57,360 --> 00:07:04,153
The last week of March she opened the
gate and eighty-three goats went down

93
00:07:04,153 --> 00:07:10,946
into the vines. The sound was not what
she expected. Steady, dry, enormous,

94
00:07:10,946 --> 00:07:17,280
hundreds of leaves at once, and somewhere
inside it, moving, the bell.

95
00:07:17,280 --> 00:07:23,299
Merle Yates farmed the two hundred acres
along her west line, fifty-six, loud, not

96
00:07:23,299 --> 00:07:28,648
a cruel man. He believed what he had
seen, and what he had seen was kudzu

97
00:07:28,648 --> 00:07:34,295
outlast a bush hog, a dozer, and two
chemical companies. He stopped his truck

98
00:07:34,295 --> 00:07:39,645
at her gate and watched the goats a
while. "Which one runs out first," he

99
00:07:39,645 --> 00:07:42,320
asked. "That kudzu, or your money.".

100
00:07:42,320 --> 00:07:47,481
In mid April she walked a paddock the
herd had stripped bare eleven days

101
00:07:47,481 --> 00:07:53,369
before. The ground had been open. She had
seen the dirt. Coming up through it now,

102
00:07:53,369 --> 00:07:58,240
in even rows down the face of the hill,
were new shoots, ankle high.

103
00:07:58,240 --> 00:08:06,294
The kudzu had not been killed. It had
been mowed. Under every stem the root

104
00:08:06,294 --> 00:08:14,565
crown sat in the ground like a closed
fist, twenty-two years of stored sugar,

105
00:08:14,565 --> 00:08:23,054
and the herd had taken only the top. Two
seasons, Burl said on the phone. Maybe

106
00:08:23,054 --> 00:08:31,107
three. Graze it, let it come, graze it
again, until the root spends what it

107
00:08:31,107 --> 00:08:31,760
saved.

108
00:08:31,760 --> 00:08:37,284
The other thing happened the same week.
There was an old hand-dug well below the

109
00:08:37,284 --> 00:08:42,529
barn, on no plat, and the vines had grown
a lid across its mouth that looked

110
00:08:42,529 --> 00:08:48,194
exactly like ground. One of the yearlings
went through. They worked past dark with

111
00:08:48,194 --> 00:08:53,718
rope and a light, and Burl came, and it
was not enough, and near midnight he put

112
00:08:53,718 --> 00:08:59,243
his hand flat on the winch and said her
name once, quietly. They filled the well

113
00:08:59,243 --> 00:09:01,760
the next morning with rock and clay.

114
00:09:01,760 --> 00:09:05,590
That night she sat at the kitchen table
with the ledger from her old work, the

115
00:09:05,590 --> 00:09:09,520
one built for writing down what a loss
was worth, and this time she did not know

116
00:09:09,520 --> 00:09:11,360
what to put in the right-hand column.

117
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:16,288
By the last week of October the east
slope had been eaten down to the shape of

118
00:09:16,288 --> 00:09:17,440
the land under it.

119
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:22,622
The goats had worked that hillside in
rotation since August, four paddocks,

120
00:09:22,622 --> 00:09:28,364
moved every nine days, and what they left
behind looked less like pasture than like

121
00:09:28,364 --> 00:09:34,106
a room stripped of its wallpaper. Corinne
walked it on a Tuesday morning with frost

122
00:09:34,106 --> 00:09:39,497
still holding in the low spots. Dead
vines hung off the fence wire in dry gray

123
00:09:39,497 --> 00:09:45,169
ropes. And standing up out of the chewed
ground, straight, pale, wider around than

124
00:09:45,169 --> 00:09:47,200
she could reach, were trunks.

125
00:09:47,200 --> 00:09:51,503
She had walked past them all summer.
Under the green ceiling they had been

126
00:09:51,503 --> 00:09:56,160
shapes in a wall of leaves, no different
from the old cattle chute, no different

127
00:09:56,160 --> 00:09:59,520
from the well the vines had covered until
a goat found it.

128
00:09:59,520 --> 00:10:03,920
She counted them twice, the second time
with her hand on each one.

129
00:10:03,920 --> 00:10:04,800
Nine.

130
00:10:04,800 --> 00:10:10,091
Burl came up the slope that afternoon,
put his palm flat on the bark, and said

131
00:10:10,091 --> 00:10:15,451
the word before she could ask for it.
Pecan. Not young ones, either. He stepped

132
00:10:15,451 --> 00:10:20,948
off the distance between the first two,
forty feet, then the next two, forty feet

133
00:10:20,948 --> 00:10:26,514
again, and the grid ran on into the vines
where the clearing stopped. Somebody had

134
00:10:26,514 --> 00:10:31,530
planted an orchard on this hill and
walked away from it, and the trees had

135
00:10:31,530 --> 00:10:36,340
gone on standing in the dark for
twenty-two years the way a pecan will,

136
00:10:36,340 --> 00:10:41,837
because a pecan can live past a hundred
years and has no interest in the plans of

137
00:10:41,837 --> 00:10:43,280
whoever put it there.

138
00:10:43,280 --> 00:10:49,230
The wind came up the slope smelling of
husks. That sharp green-shell smell. The

139
00:10:49,230 --> 00:10:53,120
goats had left the split pecan hulls
where they lay.

140
00:10:53,120 --> 00:10:54,960
Then Burl crouched down.

141
00:10:54,960 --> 00:11:00,977
Around the base of the nearest tree, at
about the height of a goat's shoulder,

142
00:11:00,977 --> 00:11:07,306
the bark was gone. Not scraped. Taken, in
a clean band all the way around, down to

143
00:11:07,306 --> 00:11:08,400
pale wet wood.

144
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:13,666
A tree feeds itself through a thin living
layer just under its bark. Cut that band

145
00:11:13,666 --> 00:11:18,933
the whole way around and nothing travels
between the leaves and the roots anymore.

146
00:11:18,933 --> 00:11:23,614
The tree stands through the winter
looking like a tree. It will even leaf

147
00:11:23,614 --> 00:11:27,970
out one more spring on what it has
stored, and then it dies with its

148
00:11:27,970 --> 00:11:28,880
branches full.

149
00:11:28,880 --> 00:11:34,560
Three of the nine were ringed most of the
way around. One was ringed all the way.

150
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:38,960
"They can't tell," Burl said. "A goat
don't know the difference between what

151
00:11:38,960 --> 00:11:43,419
you turned her out here to eat and what
you'd give anything to keep. It's all

152
00:11:43,419 --> 00:11:44,240
bark to her.".

153
00:11:44,240 --> 00:11:49,621
Fixing it cost her twice. Welded wire
cylinders around all nine trunks, staked

154
00:11:49,621 --> 00:11:55,002
deep, tall enough that a doe up on her
hind legs could not reach over the top,

155
00:11:55,002 --> 00:12:00,314
and that was money already promised to
winter hay. The exclusion fence around

156
00:12:00,314 --> 00:12:05,625
the grove pulled four acres out of the
rotation, and they were the four acres

157
00:12:05,625 --> 00:12:11,286
the herd had been clearing fastest. Every
day the goats spent somewhere else was a

158
00:12:11,286 --> 00:12:14,640
day the kudzu on that slope got back on
its feet.

159
00:12:14,640 --> 00:12:21,780
She built it anyway, through November,
mostly in the rain, with Otis handing up

160
00:12:21,780 --> 00:12:24,160
the staples one at a time.

161
00:12:24,160 --> 00:12:31,203
He named the biggest one Big Tuesday,
because Tuesday was the day they found

162
00:12:31,203 --> 00:12:37,120
it. He was nine years old that fall, and
that was reason enough.

163
00:12:37,120 --> 00:12:43,384
Those nine trees had not given her a
single nut. What they had given her was a

164
00:12:43,384 --> 00:12:46,720
reason not to sell the place that winter.

165
00:12:46,720 --> 00:12:51,523
Ground like that — written off, grown
over, offered three times to nobody —

166
00:12:51,523 --> 00:12:56,325
sits in nearly every county in this
country, and whatever is standing under

167
00:12:56,325 --> 00:13:01,517
it has been standing there a while. Tell
us where you are watching from. Put your

168
00:13:01,517 --> 00:13:02,880
town in the comments.

169
00:13:02,880 --> 00:13:07,804
Dr. Nadine Croft drove out the second
Thursday in January with a soil probe

170
00:13:07,804 --> 00:13:10,000
rattling in the bed of her truck.

171
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:15,352
She was the county extension agent, in
her forties, raised on a dairy farm one

172
00:13:15,352 --> 00:13:20,288
county east, and her work was telling
farmers the truth about their dirt

173
00:13:20,288 --> 00:13:25,293
whether they wanted it or not. Corinne
had called in October and again in

174
00:13:25,293 --> 00:13:30,645
November and gotten nowhere, until she
stopped asking for an opinion and asked

175
00:13:30,645 --> 00:13:36,206
for a test she would pay for. Letterhead
was the only language the courthouse had

176
00:13:36,206 --> 00:13:37,040
ever spoken.

177
00:13:37,040 --> 00:13:42,294
They pulled cores all morning. Fifteen
from the paddocks the goats had grazed

178
00:13:42,294 --> 00:13:47,687
twice, fifteen from a strip along the
north fence still shut in under the green

179
00:13:47,687 --> 00:13:48,240
ceiling.

180
00:13:48,240 --> 00:13:51,280
The soil report came the first week of
February.

181
00:13:51,280 --> 00:13:57,216
Organic matter in the grazed paddock ran
three point one percent. In the untouched

182
00:13:57,216 --> 00:14:03,079
strip, two point four. Nitrate nitrogen
came back at twenty-six parts per million

183
00:14:03,079 --> 00:14:08,356
against eighteen. Eighty-two goats
crossing a hillside all summer had put

184
00:14:08,356 --> 00:14:13,120
more back into that soil than she could
have hauled in on a truck.

185
00:14:13,120 --> 00:14:14,960
That part she had hoped for.

186
00:14:14,960 --> 00:14:19,710
Nadine turned the page over, set her
finger on the control column, and said

187
00:14:19,710 --> 00:14:24,782
that was the number worth looking at. For
soil that had seen no plow, no cattle,

188
00:14:24,782 --> 00:14:29,853
and no fertilizer since before Corinne
was married, the nitrogen had no business

189
00:14:29,853 --> 00:14:30,880
being that high.

190
00:14:30,880 --> 00:14:37,133
Kudzu is a legume. Same family as beans
and field peas. Down on its roots it

191
00:14:37,133 --> 00:14:43,469
carries nodules of bacteria that pull
nitrogen out of the air and fix it into

192
00:14:43,469 --> 00:14:50,055
the ground, and the kudzu had been doing
that across one hundred and four acres,

193
00:14:50,055 --> 00:14:52,640
every season, without stopping.

194
00:14:52,640 --> 00:14:53,760
Twenty-two years.

195
00:14:53,760 --> 00:14:57,646
The thing that had made the land
worthless had been feeding it the whole

196
00:14:57,646 --> 00:14:57,920
time.

197
00:14:57,920 --> 00:15:02,443
Corinne started a proper ledger that
winter — dates, paddock numbers, days

198
00:15:02,443 --> 00:15:07,090
grazed, what the goats would not eat.
Twelve years of pricing other people's

199
00:15:07,090 --> 00:15:11,922
losses had left her good at exactly one
thing, and now the thing being measured

200
00:15:11,922 --> 00:15:12,480
was hers.

201
00:15:12,480 --> 00:15:19,381
The money went out and none came in. Six
hundred dollars of hay in December. A vet

202
00:15:19,381 --> 00:15:26,366
call at two in the morning for a doe with
pneumonia. Mineral, diesel, wire, a fence

203
00:15:26,366 --> 00:15:32,330
charger after lightning found the old
one. Otis had learned to count to

204
00:15:32,330 --> 00:15:38,719
eighty-two, and then backward from it,
and did it out loud at the gate every

205
00:15:38,719 --> 00:15:45,364
evening. He had learned that number the
week they filled the well, and he never

206
00:15:45,364 --> 00:15:47,920
once counted to the other one.

207
00:15:47,920 --> 00:15:53,765
In the shed one afternoon, looking for
fence pliers, she moved a tarp and found

208
00:15:53,765 --> 00:15:59,460
Nolan's toolbox. Green, dented, his
handwriting on a strip of tape across the

209
00:15:59,460 --> 00:16:05,305
lid. The sockets still lay in the order
he had left them. She shut the lid, set

210
00:16:05,305 --> 00:16:10,400
it back on the shelf, and finished the
fence with the pliers she had.

211
00:16:10,400 --> 00:16:16,037
Burl came by at the end of the month with
a sack of mineral he said he had bought

212
00:16:16,037 --> 00:16:21,462
by mistake. Under his arm was a Bible,
black, the cover gone soft as cloth. It

213
00:16:21,462 --> 00:16:26,746
had been his wife's. He put it on the
kitchen table, opened it to a page she

214
00:16:26,746 --> 00:16:32,242
had marked in pencil years before, and
left it lying open while he talked about

215
00:16:32,242 --> 00:16:33,440
the price of hay.

216
00:16:33,440 --> 00:16:38,000
I will restore to you the years that the
locust hath eaten.

217
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:40,800
He took the empty feed sack with him when
he went.

218
00:16:40,800 --> 00:16:46,360
The county would come walk this ground in
the spring after next and write it down

219
00:16:46,360 --> 00:16:51,433
as a working farm or as nothing. Two
growing seasons. That was all she had

220
00:16:51,433 --> 00:16:51,920
bought.

221
00:16:51,920 --> 00:16:57,067
By February the only thing on the place
that had not run out was the vines. And

222
00:16:57,067 --> 00:17:00,960
the thing running out faster than her
money was the seasons.

223
00:17:00,960 --> 00:17:06,106
The sound came up the ridge before the
light did. In the last week of June, in

224
00:17:06,106 --> 00:17:11,319
the second summer, Corinne stood at the
top of the east cut and listened to the

225
00:17:11,319 --> 00:17:11,920
herd eat.

226
00:17:11,920 --> 00:17:17,091
A whole herd working a hillside of kudzu
made something closer to rain on a roof

227
00:17:17,091 --> 00:17:22,458
two fields over. Where the leaf lay thick
the tearing ran together; where the slope

228
00:17:22,458 --> 00:17:24,160
was opening it came apart.

229
00:17:24,160 --> 00:17:29,969
That summer was the third pass over the
east cut and the fourth over the barn

230
00:17:29,969 --> 00:17:36,160
slope. The first grazing takes the leaf.
The second takes what the plant shoves up

231
00:17:36,160 --> 00:17:42,198
to replace it. The third and fourth take
what it cannot spare, because every new

232
00:17:42,198 --> 00:17:47,778
canopy is paid out of sugar stored
underground, and that pocket is only so

233
00:17:47,778 --> 00:17:48,160
deep.

234
00:17:48,160 --> 00:17:54,386
By August the kudzu came back late, thin,
and low, and on the barn slope it never

235
00:17:54,386 --> 00:18:00,379
closed over the fence line. Burl set his
boot on red dirt that had not been in

236
00:18:00,379 --> 00:18:06,606
daylight for twenty-two years. He called
it the retreat, and told her not to call

237
00:18:06,606 --> 00:18:08,240
it anything stronger.

238
00:18:08,240 --> 00:18:14,040
The electric cooperative had eleven acres
of right-of-way gone to kudzu and briar,

239
00:18:14,040 --> 00:18:19,769
too steep for a bush hog and too close to
live wire for a spray crew. Six hundred

240
00:18:19,769 --> 00:18:25,283
dollars an acre, the goats hauled and
watered at her expense. Six thousand six

241
00:18:25,283 --> 00:18:28,720
hundred dollars, and the animals ate the
invoice.

242
00:18:28,720 --> 00:18:33,784
In September a burial association south
of Ellijay paid seven hundred and fifty

243
00:18:33,784 --> 00:18:38,459
dollars an acre for four acres of
headstones. In October the school board

244
00:18:38,459 --> 00:18:43,329
paid two thousand two hundred for the
bank behind the elementary ball field,

245
00:18:43,329 --> 00:18:46,640
and let the third grade out to watch the
goats work.

246
00:18:46,640 --> 00:18:51,796
Merle Yates had driven past that fence
for two seasons without stopping. That

247
00:18:51,796 --> 00:18:55,120
September he pulled onto the shoulder and
got out.

248
00:18:55,120 --> 00:19:00,513
"I laughed at you," he said. "Every man
at the feed store laughed, and I was the

249
00:19:00,513 --> 00:19:05,359
loudest, and it wasn't meanness. I
watched two men take that ground. One

250
00:19:05,359 --> 00:19:10,615
bush-hogged it a summer and quit. One
borrowed against his home place, sprayed

251
00:19:10,615 --> 00:19:15,667
two seasons, and watched it come back
thicker the third spring. A man who's

252
00:19:15,667 --> 00:19:20,240
seen two people go under doesn't clap for
the third one wading in.".

253
00:19:20,240 --> 00:19:24,662
Then he asked what she charged by the
acre for the goats, and wrote it on the

254
00:19:24,662 --> 00:19:26,000
back of a feed receipt.

255
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:31,070
The fog came the second week of
September. She went up at dawn to move

256
00:19:31,070 --> 00:19:36,948
the netting and found the paddock empty,
the gate shouldered open, white in every

257
00:19:36,948 --> 00:19:42,900
direction. She called, and the fog handed
her voice back flat. So she quit calling

258
00:19:42,900 --> 00:19:48,704
and stood still. Below her and off to the
left, farther down than she would have

259
00:19:48,704 --> 00:19:54,288
guessed, the bell. She walked toward the
bell the way a person walks toward a

260
00:19:54,288 --> 00:19:59,946
porch light, and found Pepper in a stand
of sumac with the goats bedded around

261
00:19:59,946 --> 00:20:00,240
her.

262
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:05,527
Driving home from the school job, Otis,
ten that fall, asked what she was putting

263
00:20:05,527 --> 00:20:06,320
on the bill.

264
00:20:06,320 --> 00:20:08,240
"Brush removal," she said.

265
00:20:08,240 --> 00:20:13,803
He thought about it for most of a mile.
"That's not right," he said. "We're not

266
00:20:13,803 --> 00:20:17,441
taking anything off it. We're just giving
it back.".

267
00:20:17,441 --> 00:20:22,057
That night she opened the ledger from the
old job, the one she had filled for

268
00:20:22,057 --> 00:20:26,977
twelve years with other people's losses.
For the first time since the auction, the

269
00:20:26,977 --> 00:20:30,561
number in the right-hand column had no
minus in front of it.

270
00:20:30,561 --> 00:20:36,559
Most of what gets sold as progress is
somebody in a hurry. That hill came down

271
00:20:36,559 --> 00:20:42,636
because a woman refused to hurry, one
pass at a time, while a county waited for

272
00:20:42,636 --> 00:20:48,478
her to quit. There is a kind of person
who hears go faster and slows down on

273
00:20:48,478 --> 00:20:54,321
purpose. This channel is built for them —
subscribe, and stay with this one.

274
00:20:54,321 --> 00:21:00,331
By April of the third year the east cut
was open enough to plant, and she planted

275
00:21:00,331 --> 00:21:06,341
one strip, forty feet wide and a quarter
mile long — what she could water and pay

276
00:21:06,341 --> 00:21:06,641
for.

277
00:21:06,641 --> 00:21:12,431
Thirty-eight young pecan trees went in by
hand, Otis dropping a flag at every

278
00:21:12,431 --> 00:21:18,374
stake. She did not buy an orchard. She
bought a strip, set it against the fence

279
00:21:18,374 --> 00:21:24,393
of the nine old trees, and told herself
the next slope would come next spring if

280
00:21:24,393 --> 00:21:25,841
the herd earned it.

281
00:21:25,841 --> 00:21:31,352
Nadine Croft had shown her the whip graft
on a bench in the barn until her hands

282
00:21:31,352 --> 00:21:36,792
quit shaking. In March, before the buds
moved, she took scion wood off the nine

283
00:21:36,792 --> 00:21:42,442
and kept it damp and cold until May, when
the bark slipped. Every tree she set out

284
00:21:42,442 --> 00:21:47,465
that spring carried wood from one of
those nine. Twenty-two years the old

285
00:21:47,465 --> 00:21:53,045
trees had stood covered with nothing to
show for it. Now they had children on the

286
00:21:53,045 --> 00:21:54,161
hill below them.

287
00:21:54,161 --> 00:21:59,505
None of it would feed anybody soon. A
grafted pecan needs six to ten years

288
00:21:59,505 --> 00:22:05,361
before it makes a crop worth hauling to a
buying station. The orchard on the east

289
00:22:05,361 --> 00:22:08,801
cut belonged to Otis at twenty, not Otis
at ten.

290
00:22:08,801 --> 00:22:13,829
The last week of May went dry and stayed
dry. Thirty-one days without rain, and

291
00:22:13,829 --> 00:22:18,664
the ridge end of the strip sat on the
thinnest dirt on the place. She hauled

292
00:22:18,664 --> 00:22:23,692
water in a two-hundred-gallon tank, two
trips a day, then three. By July eleven

293
00:22:23,692 --> 00:22:28,720
of the thirty-eight had gone brown to the
graft, and there is no arguing with a

294
00:22:28,720 --> 00:22:33,361
dead pecan tree. She replanted in
November and said very little about it.

295
00:22:33,361 --> 00:22:38,905
In October a white county sedan came slow
along the road above the gate, slowed

296
00:22:38,905 --> 00:22:44,590
further, and did not stop. Dean Whitcomb
was forty-four, the appraiser for Gilmer

297
00:22:44,590 --> 00:22:50,205
County — the man whose signature decided
whether a hundred and four acres were a

298
00:22:50,205 --> 00:22:55,819
farm or only dirt, and whether Corinne
kept the agricultural rate she had signed

299
00:22:55,819 --> 00:23:01,434
for or owed the county the difference. He
wrote on a clipboard against the wheel

300
00:23:01,434 --> 00:23:04,561
and drove on without putting the window
down.

301
00:23:04,561 --> 00:23:10,237
The goats worked the north slope that
fall and went out on contract twice more.

302
00:23:10,237 --> 00:23:15,913
Along the cleared fence lines the kudzu
came back every June, thinner and later

303
00:23:15,913 --> 00:23:16,641
each year.

304
00:23:16,641 --> 00:23:21,877
Burl came less that winter. He was
seventy-four, the cold got into his hip,

305
00:23:21,877 --> 00:23:26,971
and he sat on the tailgate while she
walked the paddocks. In March he was

306
00:23:26,971 --> 00:23:32,277
supposed to ride with her to the buck
sale at Ball Ground. He handed her the

307
00:23:32,277 --> 00:23:37,937
folded paper instead — his notes on width
and loin and the shape of a foot, three

308
00:23:37,937 --> 00:23:41,121
generations of judgment about goats in
pencil.

309
00:23:41,121 --> 00:23:45,919
"You know what you're looking at," he
said. "I've told you what I see. Go tell

310
00:23:45,919 --> 00:23:47,041
me what you see.".

311
00:23:47,041 --> 00:23:52,396
She came back with two bucks. He studied
them a long time and never said whether

312
00:23:52,396 --> 00:23:55,921
she had chosen right, which from Burl was
the answer.

313
00:23:55,921 --> 00:24:00,681
That spring she opened the south slope,
sixty more pecan trees, and set the

314
00:24:00,681 --> 00:24:05,698
replacements where the drought had taken
the first ones. It was the last season

315
00:24:05,698 --> 00:24:10,715
she had. The county would come out to
walk the ground and decide whether any of

316
00:24:10,715 --> 00:24:12,001
it had been farming.

317
00:24:12,001 --> 00:24:16,569
Three seasons earlier, the only thing on
that place worth counting had been the

318
00:24:16,569 --> 00:24:20,961
vines. That spring she stood at the gate
above the orchard and counted rows.

319
00:24:20,961 --> 00:24:25,575
The county truck turned in at the gate on
an April morning, and Corinne heard it

320
00:24:25,575 --> 00:24:30,072
before she saw it, because the cattle
guard at the road sounded like a dropped

321
00:24:30,072 --> 00:24:30,481
ladder.

322
00:24:30,481 --> 00:24:35,742
Dean Whitcomb changed into rubber boots
on the tailgate and said he meant to walk

323
00:24:35,742 --> 00:24:40,739
the whole thing. Otis, eleven now and
taller than the top fence wire, carried

324
00:24:40,739 --> 00:24:43,041
the camera bag without being asked.

325
00:24:43,041 --> 00:24:48,570
They started at the road bank and worked
east. Whitcomb had a form on a clipboard

326
00:24:48,570 --> 00:24:54,029
and a measuring wheel, and every so often
he stopped, wrote a figure, and took a

327
00:24:54,029 --> 00:24:59,489
photograph. He asked for stocking rates
and she gave them by season, and for the

328
00:24:59,489 --> 00:25:04,879
rotation: four acres at a time, moved on
the browse line. When he asked whether

329
00:25:04,879 --> 00:25:10,546
any of it was written down, she came back
from the truck with a binder four seasons

330
00:25:10,546 --> 00:25:10,961
thick.

331
00:25:10,961 --> 00:25:16,427
That was the old job, still working for
her. Dates, head counts, rainfall, hay

332
00:25:16,427 --> 00:25:21,041
prices, a contract for every place the
herd had been hired out to.

333
00:25:21,041 --> 00:25:25,521
He read on the tailgate a long while,
then asked to see the trees.

334
00:25:25,521 --> 00:25:30,915
The nine were up on the east shoulder,
wide-crowned now that they had light, the

335
00:25:30,915 --> 00:25:36,310
wire baskets still on the trunks. Below
them the young rows followed the contour

336
00:25:36,310 --> 00:25:41,363
in strips, three hundred and forty pecan
trees, not one within six years of

337
00:25:41,363 --> 00:25:46,347
setting a nut worth counting. On the
north line, in two draws too steep to

338
00:25:46,347 --> 00:25:51,605
fence, what was left of the kudzu still
held, and she pointed it out before he

339
00:25:51,605 --> 00:25:52,561
could find it.

340
00:25:52,561 --> 00:25:55,041
At the top of the slope he put the
clipboard down.

341
00:25:55,041 --> 00:25:59,281
"Twenty-two years," he said. "How long
did the root take?".

342
00:25:59,281 --> 00:26:02,241
"Three seasons," she said. "Four for the
rest.".

343
00:26:02,241 --> 00:26:05,761
He wrote it down and said the letter
would come from the office.

344
00:26:05,761 --> 00:26:11,360
It came in May and ran to three lines.
All one hundred and four acres were found

345
00:26:11,360 --> 00:26:17,030
to be in bona fide agricultural use, and
the covenant remained in force. That was

346
00:26:17,030 --> 00:26:22,771
the end of a clock she had been listening
to for four years. She read it twice and

347
00:26:22,771 --> 00:26:24,401
went out to move fence.

348
00:26:24,401 --> 00:26:30,097
The other envelope came at the end of
that summer. The county had revalued one

349
00:26:30,097 --> 00:26:36,015
hundred and four acres: cleared pasture,
established orchard, working water, road

350
00:26:36,015 --> 00:26:42,081
frontage. Fair market value, four hundred
sixty-two thousand eight hundred dollars.

351
00:26:42,081 --> 00:26:47,321
Nobody had offered her that. It was not a
sale price, and she of all people knew

352
00:26:47,321 --> 00:26:52,164
what an appraisal is and is not; under
the covenant her tax would still be

353
00:26:52,164 --> 00:26:57,404
figured on farm use. It was the county's
opinion of what the ground had become —

354
00:26:57,404 --> 00:27:02,711
the same ground that had stood on those
courthouse steps three times and drawn no

355
00:27:02,711 --> 00:27:03,441
bid at all.

356
00:27:03,441 --> 00:27:08,384
They knocked the nine trees in the last
week of October, with tarps and

357
00:27:08,384 --> 00:27:14,104
fiberglass poles, and Burl Tannehill sat
at the edge of it in a lawn chair telling

358
00:27:14,104 --> 00:27:19,824
Otis he was doing it wrong. The old pecan
trees had not been asked for anything in

359
00:27:19,824 --> 00:27:24,908
twenty-two years. The largest gave two
hundred and thirty-one pounds. The

360
00:27:24,908 --> 00:27:30,134
smallest, sixty-eight. Altogether, one
thousand three hundred and forty-one

361
00:27:30,134 --> 00:27:35,642
pounds, which at the buying station was
not a living. It was a receipt with her

362
00:27:35,642 --> 00:27:38,961
name on it and the word pecans above the
weight.

363
00:27:38,961 --> 00:27:44,036
She laid the assessment notice on the
kitchen table that night, beside the old

364
00:27:44,036 --> 00:27:48,914
ledger from Atlanta, the one she had
carried out of a job that priced other

365
00:27:48,914 --> 00:27:54,056
people’s ruin. Two ways of pricing the
same ground, side by side under the same

366
00:27:54,056 --> 00:27:57,681
light. She looked at them a while. Then
she made supper.

367
00:27:57,681 --> 00:28:02,891
She did not call anyone. Assessments are
public, though, and Gilmer County is a

368
00:28:02,891 --> 00:28:07,567
small place. The scale man at the feed
store had seen the poundage, and

369
00:28:07,567 --> 00:28:12,510
somebody's wife said something in a
church basement after Wednesday supper.

370
00:28:12,510 --> 00:28:17,853
By Thanksgiving every man who had laughed
on those courthouse steps had heard the

371
00:28:17,853 --> 00:28:18,321
number.

372
00:28:18,321 --> 00:28:23,121
Merle Yates heard it at the co-op, and he
did not say anything at all.

373
00:28:23,121 --> 00:28:27,014
In December she sat down with a pencil
and worked out what it would cost to

374
00:28:27,014 --> 00:28:30,801
carry the whole herd through a winter on
ground with nothing left to eat.

375
00:28:30,801 --> 00:28:35,866
The browse was gone. That had been the
whole point of the goats, and it was now

376
00:28:35,866 --> 00:28:40,997
the trouble with them. Kept out of the
orchard rows and off the young trees, the

377
00:28:40,997 --> 00:28:46,062
herd had eleven acres of standing pasture
and a hay bill that ran past what the

378
00:28:46,062 --> 00:28:51,322
lease work brought in. Burl had told her
four springs earlier that a goat is not a

379
00:28:51,322 --> 00:28:52,881
mower a person can park.

380
00:28:52,881 --> 00:28:56,881
She did not sell them off in a hurry.
That was not how she did anything.

381
00:28:56,881 --> 00:29:01,576
She kept twenty-six head, the best of the
does and two bucks, on paper as a

382
00:29:01,576 --> 00:29:06,144
breeding line and in fact because
Pepper's daughters were among them. She

383
00:29:06,144 --> 00:29:11,157
kept the lease business, which by then
was the part that actually paid. The rest

384
00:29:11,157 --> 00:29:16,233
of the goats she sold in ones and twos,
to people who asked questions before they

385
00:29:16,233 --> 00:29:17,121
asked a price.

386
00:29:17,121 --> 00:29:21,281
Merle Yates came in the second week of
December and bought nineteen.

387
00:29:21,281 --> 00:29:26,605
He stood at the fence a while before he
said anything, the way he had sat at her

388
00:29:26,605 --> 00:29:31,929
gate that first spring with the window
down. He did not apologize. Men like that

389
00:29:31,929 --> 00:29:36,849
do not, and she would not have known
where to put it. He took his cap off,

390
00:29:36,849 --> 00:29:42,375
looked up at the paddock lines, and asked
the question a man only asks after he has

391
00:29:42,375 --> 00:29:43,521
made up his mind.

392
00:29:43,521 --> 00:29:48,673
"If I wanted to do the back slope behind
my place," he said, "where would a man

393
00:29:48,673 --> 00:29:49,201
start?".

394
00:29:49,201 --> 00:29:54,922
So she told him. Nineteen head was not
enough for eight acres of vine and he

395
00:29:54,922 --> 00:30:00,795
should plan on borrowing more by July.
Electric netting, four acres at a time,

396
00:30:00,795 --> 00:30:06,440
moved before they get bored. And the
second season is the one that will get

397
00:30:06,440 --> 00:30:12,161
you, she said, because it comes back
looking exactly like a year you wasted.

398
00:30:12,161 --> 00:30:19,583
He wrote none of it down. He asked her to
say the part about the second season

399
00:30:19,583 --> 00:30:20,161
again.

400
00:30:20,161 --> 00:30:24,828
The goats went out of her trailer the way
they had come out of Burl's. She thought

401
00:30:24,828 --> 00:30:28,401
about that on the drive back and did not
mention it to anybody.

402
00:30:28,401 --> 00:30:33,627
Pepper was eleven by then, gray to the
shoulder, slow on the hill and still

403
00:30:33,627 --> 00:30:39,135
first through any gate that opened. She
was not sold. On the last Sunday of the

404
00:30:39,135 --> 00:30:44,431
year Corinne caught her in the lot,
unbuckled the worn strap, and lifted the

405
00:30:44,431 --> 00:30:49,657
brass bell off her neck for the first
time since Burl handed it to her that

406
00:30:49,657 --> 00:30:50,081
March.

407
00:30:50,081 --> 00:30:55,656
She carried it up to the orchard. The
biggest of the nine, the one Otis had

408
00:30:55,656 --> 00:31:01,457
named Big Tuesday when he was nine, had a
low limb that ran out over the mowed

409
00:31:01,457 --> 00:31:06,881
grass at about shoulder height. She hung
the bell there and let go of it.

410
00:31:06,881 --> 00:31:12,052
The wind moved it that afternoon, and it
moved on its own after that, the way

411
00:31:12,052 --> 00:31:14,161
anything hung in the open will.

412
00:31:14,161 --> 00:31:20,045
Otis was twelve. He stood with his hands
in his jacket pockets and listened a long

413
00:31:20,045 --> 00:31:20,481
while.

414
00:31:20,481 --> 00:31:23,441
"Now you can find the middle of it in the
dark," he said.

415
00:31:23,441 --> 00:31:27,937
Four springs before, the county had
offered one hundred and four acres three

416
00:31:27,937 --> 00:31:32,673
times and taken no bid, because everyone
who looked saw a hillside that had quit

417
00:31:32,673 --> 00:31:37,169
being land and turned into weather. It
was never dead ground. It was covered

418
00:31:37,169 --> 00:31:41,964
ground. That is a different word, and it
took a woman with a ledger, eighty-three

419
00:31:41,964 --> 00:31:45,681
goats, and four growing seasons to say
the difference out loud.

420
00:31:45,681 --> 00:31:50,997
The ninety-one thousand four hundred
dollars was not the expensive part. The

421
00:31:50,997 --> 00:31:56,596
expensive part was standing at a fence
for four seasons while men she had to see

422
00:31:56,596 --> 00:32:01,840
at the feed store every week made a joke
out of her, and going out the next

423
00:32:01,840 --> 00:32:04,321
morning to move the netting anyway.

424
00:32:04,321 --> 00:32:09,855
People come up the drive now and ask what
she would take for the place. She tells

425
00:32:09,855 --> 00:32:15,458
them it is not for sale, and offers them
coffee, and most stay long enough to walk

426
00:32:15,458 --> 00:32:16,081
the rows.

427
00:32:16,081 --> 00:32:20,993
The young trees are not worth anything
yet. Three hundred and forty of them, set

428
00:32:20,993 --> 00:32:25,657
in strips down a slope that used to be
one color, and none will carry a real

429
00:32:25,657 --> 00:32:30,321
crop before Otis is old enough to vote.
She knew that when she planted them.

430
00:32:30,321 --> 00:32:36,015
The bell is still on the limb. On a still
morning it does not carry as far as the

431
00:32:36,015 --> 00:32:40,001
house. On a windy one it carries all the
way to the road.

432
00:32:40,001 --> 00:32:44,792
Send this story to someone who is holding
on to a thing that everybody has told

433
00:32:44,792 --> 00:32:49,277
them to let go of. And down in the
comments, tell us about the place where

434
00:32:49,277 --> 00:32:53,761
you saw nothing but weeds, and the person
who saw something worth keeping.

